<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>lobstre.rs rss with inlined content</title><link>http://n-gate.com</link><description>webshit condom</description><lastBuildDate>Mon, 04 Oct 2021 06:59:59 -0500</lastBuildDate><item><title>Removing my site from Google search</title><link>https://www.btao.org/2021/10/03/removing-from-google/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/kzas58/removing_my_site_from_google_search"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sun, 03 Oct 2021 12:53:55 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Do you practice?</title><link>https://lobste.rs/s/h45sn7/do_you_practice</link><description>&lt;p&gt;In his talk &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4B00hV3wmMY&amp;amp;t=997s" rel="ugc"&gt;Solving the Right Problems for Engine Programmers&lt;/a&gt; Mike Acton’s first segment is about how new programmers are usually incompetent in three fundamental ways: practice, reasonable defaults, and problem solving.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;He goes on to say that most programmers do not practice, i.e., they do not take time out of their schedule to practice using the tools (languages, APIs, databases, whatever). I’ve been thinking about this for a while and it seems that a lot of professions have practice, but in the tech industry we don’t, we mostly go with sink or swim.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So my question is: do you have a regular practice? What is it like? Do you have tips and hints and recommendations for others?&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sun, 03 Oct 2021 08:53:40 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Simple Lists: a tiny to-do list app written the old-school way (server-side Go, no JS)</title><link>https://benhoyt.com/writings/simple-lists/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/paulo7/simple_lists_tiny_do_list_app_written_old"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sun, 03 Oct 2021 13:18:29 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>The hunt for a better Dockerfile</title><link>https://matduggan.com/the-hunt-for-a-better-dockerfile/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/jfcnvn/hunt_for_better_dockerfile"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sun, 03 Oct 2021 13:09:56 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Plan 9 Desktop Guide</title><link>https://pspodcasting.net/dan/blog/2019/plan9_desktop.html#intro</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/rgch76/plan_9_desktop_guide"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sun, 03 Oct 2021 17:34:35 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Realtek wireless firmwares imported</title><link>https://undeadly.org/cgi?action=article;sid=20211004070841</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/ock4oo/realtek_wireless_firmwares_imported"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Mon, 04 Oct 2021 02:54:19 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>Dune: A shell by the beach</title><link>https://github.com/adam-mcdaniel/dune</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://lobste.rs/s/iqnasv/dune_shell_by_beach"&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description><pubDate>Sun, 03 Oct 2021 15:48:07 -0500</pubDate></item><item><title>How Big Tech Runs Tech Projects and the Curious Absence of Scrum</title><link>https://blog.pragmaticengineer.com/project-management-at-big-tech/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a hr